<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ881108-0168 </DOCNO><HL> Notable andamp; Quotable </HL><SO> </SO><DATELINE> &quot;An election is a moral horror, as bad as a battle except for the blood: a mud bath for every soul concerned.&quot;  </DATELINE><TEXT>    George Bernard Shaw   &quot;I have never regarded politics as the arena of morals. It is the arena of interests.&quot; -- Aneurin Bevan   &quot;Politics, n. A strife of interests masquerading as a contest of principles.&quot; -- Ambrose Bierce, &quot;The Devil's Dictionary&quot;   &quot;All political parties die at last of swallowing their own lies.&quot; -- John Arbuthnot   &quot;Americans detest all lies except lies spoken in public or printed lies.&quot; -- Edgar Watson Howe   &quot;In order to become the master, the politician poses as the servant.&quot; -- Charles de Gaulle   &quot;Politicians are the same all over. They promise to build a bridge even when there is no river.&quot; -- Nikita S. Khrushchev   &quot;Football strategy does not originate in a scrimmage: It is useless to expect solutions in a political campaign.&quot; -- Walter Lippmann &quot;A Preface to Politics&quot;   &quot;The budget is a mythical bean bag. Congress votes mythical beans into it, and then tries to reach in and pull real beans out.&quot; -- Will Rogers   &quot;Christmas is a time when kids tell Santa what they want and adults pay for it. Deficits are when adults tell the government what they want -- and the kids pay for it.&quot; -- Richard Lamm   &quot;As quickly you start spending federal money in large amounts, it looks like free money.&quot; -- Dwight D. Eisenhower   &quot;The point to remember is that what government gives it must first take away.&quot; -- John S. Coleman   &quot;In politics a week is a very long time.&quot;  -- Harold Wilson   ---   Compiled by Blake Fleetwood, N.Y.C. </TEXT></DOC>